    "id": 166,
    "title": "Era of Jeroboam II in Israel",
    "introduction": "For the next 60 years, the kingdoms of Israel and Judah continued their spiritual decline. Nothing seemed to stop them blindly marching towards disaster—Israel, in particular, indulged in the worship of Baal and idols. In the south, Amaziah's rule was relatively successful, but he too erected idols after his successful campaign against the Edomites.\n\nUnder Jeroboam II, Israel would achieve great military success, bringing prosperity. But during Jeroboam's reign, at least three prophets would speak out against the growing spiritual and moral decay. Jonah would be sent by God to Nineveh as a special messenger to the Assyrians; Hosea would criticize Israel's idolatry; and Amos would speak out against religious formalism and social injustice. It was becoming increasingly clear that God's patience was wearing thin, and the day of Israel's captivity was imminent.\n\nAn event during this period, occurring at Elisha's tomb, proved to be a rather ironic experience—at least for those not actually involved! The deeper, more serious meaning of this event may be related to Elisha's impending fulfillment of his prophecy about defeating the Syrians, and the rebirth of a dead nation.",
